<p>I&#8217;ve followed your exchanges with ["maymay"] and I&#8217;m impressed by the thoughtfulness with which you both discuss your positions. As I read your most recent comment it occured to me that in the KFA community things are in fact different, at least to some significant degree, from the way they are in the dominant culture. For example, women are not only valued for their ability to conform to conventional standards of beauty. In fact women are valued for themselves despite embodying a wide range of appearances and identities. In addition, they are NOT viewed as sluts when they &#8220;have sex like men.&#8221; Nor are men viewed as less-than-men if they &#8220;have sex like women.&#8221; I have often wondered if the fact that so many of us do keep our sexualities private is a major part of the problem &#8211; that is, that such privacy allows the mass-media-generated dominant-culture images (which we all seem to agree are limiting at best) to be taken as &#8220;natural&#8221; or at least as &#8220;inevitable.&#8221; </p>
